			<div class="article-title col-sm-offset-2 col-sm-8 pv-sm">
				<h1 class="txt-f4 txt-s7 balance-text">Down or out: The future of fossil fuels at COP28</h1>
			</div>
			<div class="article-author pv-md col-sm-offset-3 col-sm-6">
															<a class="txt-dn txt-f1 txt-s3 txt-tu" href="/the-interpreter/contributors/articles/michelle-lyons">
							Michelle Lyons
						</a>
											<a class="txt-dn txt-f1 txt-s3 txt-tu" href="/the-interpreter/contributors/articles/ryan-neelam">
							Ryan Neelam
						</a>
												</div>
							<div class="article-summary col-sm-offset-1 col-sm-10">
					<p class="txt-s5 txt-f1 balance-text txt-lmd">
						Record attendance by oil, coal and gas lobbyists shows how seriously the industry is taking this conference – and the gap remaining to any deal.
					</p>
				</div>
					</div>

		<div class="article-main-image">
			<img class="article-main-image-img" src="https://www.lowyinstitute.org/sites/default/files/styles/interpreter_article_image/public/2023-12/53390112002_d9693371e4_k.jpg?itok=ID-z_xyF" alt="The controversial figure at the centre of negotiations is COP28 President Sultan Al Jaber, also head of the United Arab Emirates state-owned oil company ADNOC (Christopher Pike/UNFCCC/Flickr)">
              <div class="article-save-btn">
          
